{"title_page": "Teach the Future", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| full_name           = Teach the Future Campaign\n| logo                = Teach_the_Future_Campaign_-_New.png\n| named_after         = The 2nd UKSCN Demand\n| formation           = 12 October 2019\n| type                = Campaign\n| purpose             = Climate Crisis Education and Education System Reform\n| region              = United Kingdom\n| parent_organization = UK Student Climate Network and SOS-UK\n| subsidiaries        = Teach the Future Scotland\n| staff               = 8\n| volunteers          = 35 (as of April 2020)\n| website             = https://www.teachthefuture.uk\n}}\n\n'''Teach the Future''' (TtF) is the [[UK Student Climate Network]] (UKSCN) and [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|Students Organising for Sustainability]] (SOS-UK) joint campaign to repurpose the education system around the climate emergency and ecological crisis. It is formed by a volunteer base of students studying across the UK at all levels of education - from secondary to tertiary - who believe the majority of teaching and learning throughout the entirety of the education system is misaligned from the systemic changes urgently required to make to society sustainable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthefuture.uk/about|title=Who we are|website=Teach the Future|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Teach the Future campaign began as a demand of the [[UK Student Climate Network]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukscn.org/our-demands/|title=Our demands|website=UK Student Climate Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and has been so since its formation in December 2018. From this, as it was a specialist area, the demand evolved intro an individual campaign with the support of its parent organisation, Student Organising for Sustainability - UK in addition to UKSCNs School Group Developmental working group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukscn.org/ukscn-schools/|title=Schools|website=UK Student Climate Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn accordance to the third demand, the student volunteers and a professional legislative draftsperson drafted the first ever student written education [[Private member's bill|Private Members Bill]] in history<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sustainability.nus.org.uk/resources/climate-emergency-education-act-teach-the-future|title=Climate Emergency Education Act - Teach the Future @ Sustainability|website=sustainability.nus.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> which has been supported by many [[Member of parliament|Parliamentarians]]. [[Nadia Whittome]] supported the students in hosting a parliamentary reception to unveil this legislation to the Government by being their Parliamentary Sponsor<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://naee.org.uk/february-24th-2020/|title=February 24th 2020|last=Team|first=NAEE Web|date=2020-02-24|website=UK NAEE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>; this reception was held in the [[Palace of Westminster|Houses of Parliament]]'s Terrace Pavilion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.englishforums.com/news/educated-people-harms-the-environment/|title=Educated people harms the environment, declares a student activist|last=Abel|first=Daniel|date=2020-02-26|website=English Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> on 26th February 2020 and had an attendance of over 200 politicians, educators, student campaigners, union representatives and supporters.  \n\n== Asks ==\nTeach the Future calls for six main asks from the government<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthefuture.uk/asks|title=Asks|website=Teach the Future|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wonkette.com/uk-teens-tired-of-waiting-for-climate-education-so-they-drafted-a-law-to-require-it|title=UK Teens Tired Of Waiting For Climate Education, So They Drafted A Law To Require It|date=2020-02-12|website=Wonkette|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n# A government commissioned review into how the English formal education system is preparing students for the climate emergency and ecological crisis\n# The inclusion of the climate emergency and ecological crisis in English teaching standards and training\n# The enactment of an English Climate Emergency Education Act - the first student written bill in history<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tickle|first=Louise|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/feb/11/pupils-draft-climate-bill-anxiety-lack-guidance-schools|title=Pupils draft their own climate bill as anxiety grows over lack of guidance for schools|date=2020-02-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n# The establishment of a national climate emergency youth voice grant\n# The establishment of a national Youth Climate Endowment Fund\n# For all new state-funded educational buildings to be built carbon net-zero from 2020 onwards and for all existing state-funded educational buildings to be converted to a carbon net-zero grid by 2030\n\n== Structure ==\nTeach the Future is a non-hierarchal organisation currently run by a team of  3 volunteers - spread across the country; in addition the campaign secured funding and has just finished their recruitment process, now employing 5 part-time student campaign coordinators, 1 campaign manager from SOS-UK and 2 other SOS-UK staff members on small contract hours. \n\nThese volunteers organise through an online [[Slack (software)|Slack]] workspace and aim to onboard new influxes of volunteers regularly.\n\n== Supporting organisations ==\nThe Teach the Future campaign is supported and endorsed by multiple national organisations focussing on areas such as youth representation, conservation and education system reform. They are<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthefuture.uk/post/young-people-deserve-opportunities-to-make-a-difference-and-have-their-voices-heard|title=\u201cYoung people deserve opportunities to make a difference and have their voices heard\u201d|last=Skuodas (UKSCN)|first=Mary|date=2020-02-29|website=Teach the Future|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthefuture.uk/post/supporting-the-future-with-byc|title=Supporting the Future with BYC|last=Sweetman (UKSCN)|first=Charlie|date=2020-02-21|website=Teach the Future|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthefuture.uk/post/teacher-support-for-climate-crisis-education-reform|title=Teachers for climate crisis education reform|last=member|first=N. E. U.|date=2020-02-25|website=Teach the Future|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n![https://www.actionforconservation.org Action for Conservation]\n![https://www.andbeyond.earth And Beyond]\n![https://www.architectscan.org Architects Climate Action Network]\n![http://www.ashdentrust.org.uk Ashden Trust]\n![https://www.aoc.co.uk Association of Colleges]\n![https://www.bioregional.com Bioregional]\n![[British Youth Council]]\n![https://www.cpre.org.uk Campaign to Protect Rural England]\n![[Campaign against Climate Change|Campaign Against Climate Change]]\n![[Chartered Institution of Water and Environmental Management]]\n![[Chester Zoo]]\n|-\n![https://climateoutreach.org Climate Outreach]\n![[Country Trust]]\n![https://www.eauc.org.uk Alliance for Sustainability Leadership in Education]\n![https://earthwatch.org.uk Earthwatch Insititute]\n!Force of Nature\n![[Friends of the Earth (EWNI)|Friends of the Earth]]\n![[Global Action Plan]]\n![https://www.greenschoolsproject.org.uk Green Schools Project]\n![[Greenpeace]]\n![https://www.hubbub.org.uk HubBub]\n![[Institute of Environmental Management and Assessment|IEMA]]\n|-\n|[https://weareive.org We Are IVE]\n|[[Institution of Civil Engineers|Institute of Civil Engineers]]\n|[https://www.ligc.co.uk/who-we-are Leadership in Global Change]\n|[[Landscape In