sis|last=Moore|first=Becca|date=2020-02-26|website=British Youth Council|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Featured in an article by [[Caroline Lucas|Caroline Lucas MP]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carolinelucas.com/latest/teach-the-future-on-climate-crisis|title=TEACH THE FUTURE ON CLIMATE CRISIS {{!}} Caroline Lucas|website=www.carolinelucas.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Joe Brindle on [[BBC Radio Wiltshire]]\n* Nathan Widdowson in a blog by [[Stephen Morgan (politician)|Stephen Morgan MP]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stephenmorgan.org.uk/education-is-key-to-tackling-climate-change-says-city-mp-as-he-joins-students-in-parliament-for-teach-the-future/|title=\u201cEducation is key to tackling climate change\u201d says city MP as he joins students in Parliament for Teach the Future|last=Munn|first=Jonah|website=Stephen Morgan|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Featured in an article by [[The Student Room]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestudentroom.co.uk/news/students-ask-parliament-to-teach-climate-change-issues-in-schools|title=Students ask parliament to teach climate change issues in schools {{!}} The Student Room|website=www.thestudentroom.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Mary Skuodas in an article by [[DeSmogBlog|DeSmog]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmog.co.uk/2020/02/26/our-education-system-unfit-purpose-students-call-climate-education-reform|title='Unfit for Purpose': Students Seek to Take Climate Education Into Their Own Hands|website=DeSmog UK|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Job Brindle on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]\n* Joe Brindle in an interview with [[BBC Points West]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000ftfc|title=BBC One - Points West, Evening News, 26/02/2020|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Featured in an article by [[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect Magazine]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/science-and-technology/climate-change-when-did-start-schools-study|title=Why we need to change the way we teach climate change|last=Power|first=Amanda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Charlie Sweetman and Jess Nicholls in an interview with [[The Economist]]\n* Charlie Sweetman and Karis McIntyre on [[BBC Radio Wiltshire]]\n* [[Zamzam Ibrahim]] in an article by [[The Japan Times|Japan Times]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Elks|first=Sonia|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/27/world/climate-change-greta-thunberg/|title=Schools challenged to teach climate change as students join Greta Thunberg's strikes|date=2020-02-27|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n* Charlie Sweetman and Aurora McLaughlin-Gouldhacker in an article with the [[Reuters|Thomas Reuters Foundation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.trust.org/item/20200227042400-kgt79/|title=Schools challenged to teach climate change as Greta strikes grow|last=Foundation|first=Thomson Reuters|website=news.trust.org|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Scarlett Westbrook and Joe Brindle interviewing live on BBC Breakfast<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/394656620|title=Teenage climate activists Scarlett Westbrook and Joe Brindle go live on BBC Breakfast to talk about the Teach the Future campain|website=Vimeo|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n[[Category:Climate change in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Education in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Education reform]]\n[[Category:Environmental education in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Environmental organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Student organisations in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Youth organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| full_name           = Teach the Future Campaign\n| logo                = Teach_the_Future_Campaign_-_New.png\n| named_after         = The 2nd UKSCN Demand\n| formation           = 12 October 2019\n| type                = Campaign\n| purpose             = Climate Crisis Education and English Education System Reform\n| region              = United Kingdom - specifically England\n| parent_organization = UK Student Climate Network and SOS-UK\n| staff               = 7\n| volunteers          = 35 (as of April 2020)\n| website             = https://www.teachthefuture.uk\n}}\n\n'''Teach the Future''' (TtF) is the [[UK Student Climate Network]] (UKSCN) and [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|Students Organising for Sustainability]] (SOS-UK) joint campaign to repurpose the education system around the climate emergency and ecological crisis. It is formed by a volunteer base of students studying across the UK at all levels of education - from secondary to tertiary - who believe the majority of teaching and learning throughout the entirety of the education system is misaligned from the systemic changes urgently required to make to society sustainable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthefuture.uk/about|title=Who we are|website=Teach the Future|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Teach the Future campaign began as a demand of the [[UK Student Climate Network]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukscn.org/our-demands/|title=Our demands|website=UK Student Climate Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and has been so since its formation in December 2018. From this, as it was a specialist area, the demand evolved intro an individual campaign with the support of its parent organisation, Student Organising for Sustainability - UK in addition to UKSCNs School Group Developmental working group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukscn.org/ukscn-schools/|title=Schools|website=UK Student Climate Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn accordance to the third demand, the student volunteers and a professional legislative draftsperson drafted the first ever student written education [[Private member's bill|Private Members Bill]] in history<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sustainability.nus.org.uk/resources/climate-emergency-education-act-teach-the-future|title=Climate Emergency Education Act - Teach the Future @ Sustainability|website=sustainability.nus.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> which has been supported by many [[Member of parliament|Parliamentarians]]. [[Nadia Whittome]] supported the students in hosting a parliamentary reception to unveil this legislation to the Government by being their Parliamentary Sponsor<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://naee.org.uk/february-24th-2020/|title=February 24th 2020|last=Team|first=NAEE Web|date=2020-02-24|website=UK NAEE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>; this reception was held in the [[Palace of Westminster|Houses of Parliament]]'s Terrace Pavilion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.englishforums.com/news/educated-people-harms-the-environment/|title=Educated people harms the environment, declares a student activist|last=Abel|first=Daniel|date=2020-02-26|website=English Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> on 26th February 2020 and had an attendance of over 200 politicians, educators, student campaigners, union representatives and supporters.  \n\n== Asks ==\nTeach the Future calls for six main asks from the government<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthefuture.uk/asks|title=Asks|website=Teach the Future|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wonkette.com/uk-teens-tired-of-waiting-for-climate-education-so-they-drafted-a-law-to-require-it|title=UK Teens Tired Of Waiting For Climate Education, So They Drafted A Law To Require It|date=2020-02-12|website=Wonkette|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n# A government commissioned review into how the English formal education system is preparing students for the climate emergency and ecological crisis\n# The inclusion of the climate emergency and ecological crisis in English teaching standards and training\n# The enactment of an English Climate Emergency Education Act - the first student written bill in history<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tickle|first=Louise|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/feb/11/pupils-draft-climate-bill-anxiety-lack-guidance-schools|title=Pupils draft their own climate bill as anxiety grows over lack of guidance for schools|date=2020-02-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n# The establishment of a national climate emergency youth voice grant\n# The establishment of a national Youth Climate Endowment Fund\n# For all new state-funded educational buildings to be built carbon net-zero from 2020 onwards and for all existing state-funded educational buildings to be converted to a carbon net-zero grid by 2030\n\n== Structure ==\nTeach the Future is a non-hierarchal organisation currently run by a team of over 20 volunteers - spread across the country; the campaign has secured funding and is currently in the process of employing 5 part-time campaigners (a mix of both student and seconded staff). \n\nThese volunteers organise through an online [[Slack (software)|Slack]] workspace and aim to onboard new influxes of volunteers regularly.\n\n== Supporting organisations ==\nThe Teach the Future campaign is supported and endorsed by multiple national organisations focussing on areas such as youth representation, conservation and education system reform. They are<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthefuture.uk/post/young-people-deserve-opportunities-to-make-a-difference-and-have-their-voices-heard|title=\u201cYoung people deserve opportunities to make a difference and have their voices heard\u201d|last=Skuodas (UKSCN)|first=Mary|date=2020-02-29|website=Teach the Future|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthefuture.uk/post/supporting-the-future-with-byc|title=Supporting the Future with BYC|last=Sweetma